The project¶

Analyzing the way people are looking at pictures on different environments and see if some of them seems to cause more stress.

1. We wanted to see pictures¶

We had csv data and we wanted to see patterns on the pictures.
Task: Automate the way we generated the plots

1.1 What data did we have¶

  • Subject
  • Landscape which are (see below for samples)
    • 1: Aggressive building city
    • 2: Convenient building city
    • 3: Homogene background
    • 4: Forest
    • 5: Parc
    • 6: Homogene grass
  • All the fixation, with position, time and order

1.2 Generate the plots¶

2. Analyze the raw data¶

Here we are looking for:

  • Correlation in the way people look at the landscape priority
  • Differences with the way people look at pictures

All data by landscape¶

Fixation distributions by landscape¶

3. By looking at the pictures few features might help:¶

  • Longest fixation
  • Horizontal covering (max x - min x)
  • Vertical covering
  • Standard deviation of x (how big are the moves)
  • Standard deviation of y
  • Mean of fixation
  • Number of fixation

4 ANOVA¶

5 Summary¶

  • Landscapes types 1 and 2 (plain buildings, and nice architecture) and 4 (forest) are creating more moves on the eyes.
  • Causes more stress
  • We can also notice than the covered x and y is bigger on 2, this can be explained by the fact that pictures of 2 are more sophisticated and we want to look at them more (side effect)
  • On landscapes types 3 and 6 (unicolor and grass), and also 5 a bit less (parc) we observe longer fixation, and less moves.
  • More relaxing views
  • Finally, one can notice that the std is usually bigger on the class 3 (homogene background), which means that people are looking at them in different ways (can be inverstigated for later researches)
